undly influential philosopher, this collection will become a catalyst for any future rethinking of philosophical hermeneutics, as well as a significant starting place for rereading and reviewing Hans-Georg Gadamer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aallusion.  aart.  abeing.  acollaborators.  aderrida.  aepisteme.  aepistemology.  aethics.  afascism.  agadamer.  agerman philosophy.  ahabermas.  ahegel.  aheidegger.  ahermeneutics.  ahistoricism.  alanguage.  alaw.  alevinas.  aliterature.  ametaphysics.  amoral philosophy.  amorality.  anational socialism.  anazi.  anietzsche.  anonfiction.  anothingness.  aorozco.  aphilosophy.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitical science.  apostmodernism.  aromanticism.  arorty.  asocial sciences.  asocialism.  astrauss.  athird reich.  atruth and method.  awaite.  awarnke.  azuckert.1 aBeiner, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowie, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruns, Gerald L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGadamer, Hans-Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabermas, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajewski, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarshall, Donald G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrozco, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRorty, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaite, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb